f="http://store.station.sony.com/hardgood.jsp?SKU=EQ1RE-HG-ZP0102-EQZPPO-DR100"> go</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> to make a <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://store.station.sony.com/hardgood.jsp?SKU=EQ1BN-HG-BU0202-AFBN1F-MTSGN">buck </a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->you <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/ubb/everquest/Forum1/HTML/000584.html">ask</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->?<br><br>Well, from the people who brought you the wonderful changes to <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/ubb/everquest/Forum1/HTML/000155.html">Ragefire</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->, comes the latest development, designed to basically put more money in their pockets.<br><br>Verant had originally stated a long time ago, in a galaxy apparently not ours, that they would allow players to change servers. That way if your friends started playing elsewhere...then no worries, you could join up with them. That went out the window as fast as the many other promises abandoned. (Including Brad’s inital promise of titles being given to anyone who could demonstrate any bug that effected the game economy.) Of course some of those promises were made pre-release...then shelved...and later denied, or forgotten. EverQuest has changed quite a bit from it’s <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://desslock.gamespot.com/features/everquest/interview.html">beginnings</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->. In fact, most old articles are no longer accessible on the official EQ site where they were archieved.<br><br>Moving servers was a promise denied. There were numerous reasons presented for it, mainly being cost/time and disruption/server balance.<br><br>Later the server move policy <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://store.station.sony.com/eq_char_moves/">changed</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->, allowing people to pay a fee and move to certain servers. They could even switch characters to other accounts. <br><br>With this came the inevitable opportunity for people who behaved so poorly that they needed to literally flee a server to escape their horrendous reputation. A server where they could be granted a new name, if someone else already had the character name in existence. However they were forced to wander a bit as “BobX the Asshat”. And most people realized that a naked level 60 showing up with the letter “x” at the end wasn’t originally from the server. And most people were also able to get in touch with people from the previous server. Who could then warn them about the scumbags in their midst. <br><br>Most people who took advantage of the ability to move though were not asshats. No, they were people who wanted to move to greener, less crowded pastures. <br><br>Even people who weren’t caught out inevitiably proved themselves to be scumbags, and it gets rather expensive paying for an exodus every few months, losing all your gear and moving on. <br><br>Plus half the stuff that people are total scuzzbags over involves loot. They love their loot, they fucked over many a person for it. So they have little desire to leave it, even if their reputation becomes shit. <br><br>However the latest policy change by Verant serves no real reasonable purpose for the masses. Instead it exists almost solely to help ebayers and people with piss poor reputations.<br><br>Name changes.<br><br>Yes, indeedy. Now Verant will allow anyone with $50 to change up to 8 character names.<br><br>Never mind that Bob was a total asshat who scammed and trained people...then discovered he was shut out of the high end game. Never mind that Bob attempted to flee the server, only to be caught out (as so often happened) when his reputation caught up to him.<br><br>Nope, now Bob can change his name for $50. And WHAMMO presto! A new reputation. A fresh start. And you don’t even need to give up the server you know and the gear you worked so hard to fuck others out of.<br><br>This policy exists for one reason and one reason only. To make money. Now don’t think I’m knocking making money. I’m not. (Though VI denies that’s the primary motivation on things like <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/ubb/everquest/Forum1/HTML/000235.html">charging for server moves</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->. But it’s a pretty fucking stupid thing to do when it’s at the cost of the game and the players. Unless of course you no longer have a long term vision for that game.<br><br>Verant, through it’s employees, has stated numerous times, REPEATEDLY that name changes were not supported, because this was a social game. People who petitioned in game to have their name changed were told “no”. Allowing people to change their name allowed them to escape their reputation. Therefore names would NOT be changed. The only exceptions to this was the case of the unacceptable names. Which really depended on who was enforcing it. And rarely did some asshole weasel a name change out of that.<br><br>But no problem now. Want to fuck over an entire guild, steal the bank and sell? No problem! Want to buy an account on ebay, but worry about the reputation that you’d carry with it? Even if the character had no poor reputation, you’d be known as an ebayer. No problem! Change the names.<br><br>True, it’s going to be hard for some fucker who’s level 60 and decked out in primal and other high end goodies to “remake” themselves. The high end game population is still low enough that people have a pretty good idea what gear who has at that level. Then again, most people that level of the game won’t be looking to change a name...unless they’re ebayed. However, the worst assholes (just look at the shitlist...hell look at Uzziell) are far less equipped...because they <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> are</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> assholes. They rarely get that far into the game. <br><br>No, to proceed further beyond a shit reputation one either needs to server move and pray no one finds you out. Remake a character and start over. Or work very hard, and let enough time pass that people begin to forget what an asshole you once were.<br><br>This new policy only exists because VI can make money off it. And they will. The server move program has been <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> very</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> profitable.<br><br> There are many people who would love to escape some problem in EQ and change their name. I’d even be willing to bet a large portion of them wouldn’t be assholes, but rather people who had a really bad problem with a guild, or some other people and just want to escape it. How many of them will take advantage of this change, who could say? I don’t think most would. <br><br>Yet, that’s also part of EQ. It’s part of how your character grows and develops throughout the game, because it is a social game. Your name is a representation of *<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>who you are</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->*. People have the ability to leave the server. They have the ability to make new characters and start over. <br><br>However that was a constructive <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> CONSEQUENCE</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> of one’s actions. Players have very little recourse to take action against shitheads in the game. In fact the most effective course of action is to simply avoid the worst of them like the plague and warn others about them. And that had it’s consequences. Most shitlisted people at one time or another have *begged* the moderators to remove their shitlistings. More than one has even contacted Verant about our board and the shitlist in a foolish attempt to get them to take some action against us, to force us to remove it. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br><br>Now, they don’t have to though. No more will they need to make amends for their actions.  Now someone can lie about their epic, and get away with it. They can rip off their guild and get away with it. Be a bully, force your way into that camp. It doesn’t matter, you just want to level up and get phat lewtz. Who cares? Stomp on people!! They can act like a complete sociopath, and providing a GM doesn’t personally witness specific rules being broken and ban ‘em... they’ll get away with it. All they need to do is pay $50 and get a name change. New name, new slate, no consequences.<br><br>The <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> only</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> thing this policy allows is for people to literally change their identity. <br><br>How can that possibly have a positive impact on the game?<br><br>The only positive thing I see here is VI making $50 a pop off it. <br><br>Might as well bleed that cash cow for all it’s worth. After all, when you don’t expect a game to have the same longitivity after <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://starwarsgalaxies.station.sony.com/">new</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://everquest2.station.sony.com/">competition</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.blizzard.com/wow/"> comes</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://nwn.bioware.com/"> out[/link, and <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://pc.ign.com/articles/324/324215p1.html">come out i</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> (and <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.darkageofcamelot.com/">has</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->), you might as well make all you can off it now. Since the long term consequences to the game won’t matter. When it comes out on <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.beststuff.com/article.php3?story_id=3186">Playstation2 in 2003</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->, people won’t exactly have the same expectations anyway.<br><br>The majority of people (I believe) will continue to play in the fair and honorable manner that they always have. It’s not consequences that prevent them from acting out, it’s conscience. However the number of players who do choose to act in a negative way that severely impacts other players is evident by the shitlist. And that is the number we have <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> with</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> the player-imposed consequences of <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> most</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> of them becoming social pariahs. How fun it will be for everyone else when someone who lied about their epic, ninjalooted, trained repeatedly, scammed repeatedly, etc ad naseum... can simply remove themselves from the shitlist by paying $50 for a name change?<br><br>Unfortunately to the players still playing the game, it does matter and will matter.. And it will effect them. At least until they move on and pay the same company even more money to play <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://everquest2.station.sony.com/">another one of it’s games</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->. Either way, look who <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.sonyonline.com/">wins</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->. You’re in Our World Now...<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> cha-ching!</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> <p><a href="http://marian333.livejournal.com" target="_blank"><img src="http://eqscreenshot.homestead.com/files/eq_sig_tarot.jpg" border="0"></a> <br><font style='font-size=10px'><i>Never attribute to malice, that which can be reasonably explained by stupidity.</i><br> -Spider Robinson  </FONT><p><A HREF="mailto:Marian333@hotmail.com?Subject=Lanys Board">Bitch At Tarot!</A> </p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#D5D4D5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub110.ezboard.com/uranvarian.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ranvarian</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Frogloks</span><br> <font color=#000033>(6/10/02 11:49:56 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub110.ezboard.com/feqasylumrantsandravesbalancingissues.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2623.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: No more shitlist</span><hr size=1> wo